<task id="005" project="spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r6">
  <metadata>
    <title>D-A-05 Wire `SprkChatAgentFactory.CreateAgentAsync` to Scope-Resolved Persona (Pillar 1)</title>
    <phase>Phase A — Data-driven Foundation</phase>
    <status>completed</status>
    <completed>2026-06-07</completed>
    <completion-notes>
      Pillar 1 closeout: Replaced hardcoded `BuildDefaultSystemPrompt(null)` in
      `PlaybookChatContextProvider.GetContextAsync` standalone-mode branch with
      `_scopeResolver.ResolvePersonaForChatAsync(tenantId, playbookId, ct)`. The
      factory's call chain (`SprkChatAgentFactory.CreateAgentAsync` →
      `IChatContextProvider.GetContextAsync` → provider) now produces a
      byte-identical system prompt when no tenant CUST- override exists (FR-04
      binding via the seeded SYS-DEFAULT row from task 004).

      Decision (smallest change to meet FR-04 per parent agent guidance): only
      the standalone-mode branch (playbookId==null) was cut over to the resolver.
      The named-playbook branches (lines 178/186) continue to call
      `BuildDefaultSystemPrompt(playbookName)` because that text is runtime-dynamic
      (interpolates playbook name). Wiring those to the playbook-attached persona
      variant is out of scope for Pillar 1 closure.

      Decision (legacy method retention): `BuildDefaultSystemPrompt()` is RETAINED
      as a null-safety/exception fallback ONLY. When the resolver throws
      `InvalidOperationException` (catastrophic SYS- seed-data failure per task
      003's contract) OR returns null/empty (contract violation), the provider
      emits a CRITICAL log and falls back to the legacy text to preserve chat
      availability while loudly signaling the deployment gap. This satisfies
      project CLAUDE.md "MUST NOT hardcode persona text" — the static text is
      no longer the primary source; it's a deployment-failure safety net.

      Files: 1 production (`PlaybookChatContextProvider.cs`), 1 new test file
      (`SprkChatAgentFactoryPersonaTests.cs`, 4 tests). Build: 0 errors, 16
      pre-existing warnings. Tests: 4/4 new + 35/35 existing PlaybookChatContextProvider
      + 18/18 SprkChatAgentFactory + 92/92 related = all green. Publish-size
      delta: +1,968 bytes (~0.002 MB) vs task-002 baseline (well under ≤+5 MB
      R6 budget; 45.50 MB current vs 60 MB ceiling per NFR-02).

      ADR/NFR compliance: ADR-010 (no new DI), ADR-013 (facade boundary
      preserved — resolver is AI-internal), ADR-015 (no user message content
      logged), ADR-029 (publish hygiene), NFR-01 (conversational primacy —
      ChatContext shape unchanged by persona swap), NFR-10 (8K budget
      unchanged), NFR-13 (safety pipeline untouched), FR-03 (most-specific-wins
      via task 003 resolver), FR-04 (byte-identical with no override). All
      verified via tests + manual code review.

      Completion notes: `projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r6/notes/task-005-completion.md`
    </completion-notes>
    <estimated-effort>5 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>002, 003, 004</dependencies>
    <blocks>028</blocks>
    <tags>bff-api, ai, chat, scope</tags>
    <rigor-hint>FULL</rigor-hint>
    <rigor-reason>Modifies `.cs` in chat-agent core path; removes hardcoded `BuildDefaultSystemPrompt()` call site (binding cutover); NFR-01 conversational primacy bound; multi-task dependency.</rigor-reason>
    <parallel-group>none</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
    <parallel-reason>Independent factory file; no contention with other Phase A tasks at this point.</parallel-reason>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Replace the hardcoded `BuildDefaultSystemPrompt()` call site in
    `SprkChatAgentFactory.CreateAgentAsync` with a call to
    `IScopeResolverService.ResolvePersonaForChatAsync(tenantId, playbookId?)` (added in
    task 003). The resolver returns the most-specific-wins persona; the factory uses its
    `systemPrompt` field in the system-prompt assembly. With the SYS-DEFAULT row seeded
    (task 004), behavior MUST be identical to today for tenants with no override (FR-04
    binding).

    Critical-path context: this task is the Pillar 1 cutover. After it lands, tenant admins
    can change the chat-agent voice by creating a CUST- persona row in Power Apps — no
    code deploy required. NFR-01 conversational primacy binding: the resolver augments the
    system prompt but the agent ALWAYS retains conversational ability regardless of which
    persona is resolved. Persona is the voice; conversation flow is intrinsic.

    Per project CLAUDE.md "MUST NOT hardcode persona text in C# after Pillar 1 lands" —
    `BuildDefaultSystemPrompt()` MUST be either deleted OR retained ONLY as a dev-time
    fallback that asserts the resolver returned non-null (with a CRITICAL log + bug report).
    Decide which path during implementation; document in task notes.

    Regression test required: side-by-side comparison of CreateAgentAsync output before
    and after the cutover, with no overrides in place, MUST produce byte-identical system
    prompts.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior BFF engineer with deep familiarity with `SprkChatAgentFactory.CreateAgentAsync`,
    the chat-agent system prompt assembly, NFR-01 conversational primacy contract, and the
    `IScopeResolverService` resolver pattern.
  </role>

  <goal>
    `SprkChatAgentFactory.CreateAgentAsync` invokes `ResolvePersonaForChatAsync` and uses
    the returned `systemPrompt`. With no tenant or playbook override in place, the
    assembled system prompt is byte-identical to pre-cutover output. A regression test
    asserts the equality. Build green; publish-size delta reported; ADR + NFR compliance
    verified.
  </goal>

